scenes.alt:
Eden's eating is transgression punished;
Luffy's is the founding grace of a heroic arc - no prohibition was violated, no shame follows. Genesis is a fall; One Piece is a call. To hold the homology you have to read the Fall as felix culpa - the fortunate fall, the fault that's a precondition for the whole redemptive story - which Christian tradition already offers you. Under felix culpa the two snap together much harder: the loss of the sea/Garden is the price of a destiny that couldn't otherwise exist.

The residue that won't dissolve: Eden is about knowing, One Piece is about becoming. You can squint knowledge into initiation, but the epistemic core of Genesis (their eyes were opened) has no real analogue - Luffy notably does not become more self-aware or ashamed. If anything he's the anti-Adam: eats the fruit, gains power, feels no nakedness.
